    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So if I'm setting up a new intern with access to the company's shared drives and some internal software, what are some specific ways I should actually enforce that? Like, what are the actual steps for setting it up so they don't have too much power?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Start by creating a dedicated user account specifically for the intern instead of reusing the admin's login credentials. Assign them only the permissions required for their tasks, which might include read-write access to a specific shared drive and user-level access to one internal application. Never grant administrative rights, sudo privileges, or access to sensitive databases like HR or payroll until they have completed their training and passed background checks. This granular approach ensures that even if their account is compromised, the damage is limited to just what they were allowed to see.",
